MetricMind Project - Day 3 Plan

Goal for Day 3

Yesterday we built the stg_sales model with margin calculated correctly. Today we build the Semantic Layer — the most important part of this whole project. This is the piece that makes your AI trustworthy.

What is a Semantic Layer? (In Simple Words)

Think of it like a dictionary for your company's numbers. Instead of every person (or AI) writing their own formula for "Revenue" or "Margin," we write it ONE time in a special file. Everyone — humans, dashboards, and the AI agent — must use this same definition. No more different numbers for the same question.

We will use Cube.dev (free, open-source) for this.


Step 1: Install Cube.dev

You need Node.js installed first (v18 or higher). Then run:

npx cubejs-cli create metricmind_cube -d duckdb

This creates a new folder called metricmind_cube with Cube's starter files.


Step 2: Connect Cube to Your DuckDB Database

Open the .env file inside metricmind_cube/ and set:

CUBEJS_DB_TYPE=duckdb
CUBEJS_DB_DUCKDB_DATABASE_PATH=../metricmind.duckdb

(Adjust the path so it points to the metricmind.duckdb file from Day 2.)


Step 3: Define Your Semantic Model (The Important Part)

Inside metricmind_cube/model/cubes/, create a file called sales.yml.

This file below is the actual Cube.dev semantic layer definition file — use it as your model:

yamlcubes:
  - name: sales
    sql_table: stg_sales

    dimensions:
      - name: order_id
        sql: order_id
        type: number
        primary_key: true

      - name: region
        sql: region
        type: string

      - name: product_category
        sql: product_category
        type: string

      - name: quarter
        sql: quarter
        type: string

      - name: year
        sql: year
        type: number

      - name: date
        sql: date
        type: time

    measures:
      - name: total_revenue
        sql: revenue
        type: sum

      - name: total_material_cost
        sql: material_cost
        type: sum

      - name: total_shipping_cost
        sql: shipping_cost
        type: sum

      - name: total_margin
        sql: margin
        type: sum

      - name: order_count
        sql: order_id
        type: count

What this file does:


dimensions = things you can group or filter by (region, quarter, category, date)
measures = numbers you can calculate (total revenue, total margin, order count)
This file is the single source of truth. No matter who asks "what is total margin," the answer always comes from this exact formula.



Step 4: Start Cube.dev

cd metricmind_cube
npm run dev

This starts the Cube API and a Playground UI at http://localhost:4000.


Step 5: Test the Semantic Layer

In the Cube Playground, try asking for:


sales.total_revenue grouped by sales.region
sales.total_margin grouped by sales.quarter


Check the JSON response tab. Confirm it returns clean, correct JSON like this:

json{
  "data": [
    { "sales.region": "Europe", "sales.total_revenue": "125430.50" },
    { "sales.region": "Asia", "sales.total_revenue": "98120.75" },
    { "sales.region": "US", "sales.total_revenue": "110200.10" }
  ]
}

This proves your Semantic Layer works — it always gives the same number for "European revenue," no matter who asks or how many times.


